# Phase 9.Z.B / task #124 — D5 heap + wall-time measurements
# CPU strip pool walker (incremental landing matching GPU's current state)

## Run conditions

- Host: water-cooled AMD Ryzen 9 7950X (16 cores / 32 threads)
- RAM: 128 GB DDR5
- Kernel: Linux 6.6.114.1-microsoft-standard-WSL2
- Rust: build via `cargo build --release` on `benchmarks/heaptrack/drivers/cpu_profile`
- Driver: `target/release/cpu-profile` (commit will be the D5 landing commit)
- Heaptrack: 1.3.0 (`/usr/bin/heaptrack`)
- Synthetic XorShift sRGB pair via `synth_pair(w, h)` in driver
- Strip body height: `STRIP_H_BODY = 512` (matches GPU default)

## Methodology

1. For each (size, mode) cell:
   - Run under heaptrack: `heaptrack -o <name> target/release/cpu-profile cvvdp <mode> <w> <h>`.
   - Run again without heaptrack: `target/release/cpu-profile cvvdp <mode> <w> <h>`.
   - Extract peak heap from heaptrack .zst via
     `heaptrack_print <file>.zst | grep "peak heap"`.
2. Captured both `t_score_ms_heaptrack` (under preload) and
   `t_score_ms_no_heaptrack` (clean run). Heaptrack's per-alloc
   instrumentation magnifies the strip walker's extra accumulator
   `f32::powf` operations — the clean-run wall times are what
   production code sees.

## Findings (honest report)

**Memory impact: ZERO.** Strip mode peak heap is bit-identical to
Full mode at every size (1MP: 295.81M, 4MP: 1.18G, 16MP: 4.73G).
warm_ref_strip is bit-identical to warm_ref (1MP: 230.78M, 4MP:
922.85M, 16MP: 3.69G).

This matches the GPU's currently-shipped strip walker
("Phase 3 Approach B incremental landing" per
`crates/cvvdp-gpu/docs/STRIP_PROCESSING.md:281-320`). On both CPU
and GPU today, only the pool stage iterates in strips; the weber
pyramid build + CSF apply + masking + mult-mutual chain remain
full-image-sized.

The targets the brief specified (`≤ 1.6 GB at 40 MP for strip`,
`≤ 2.0 GB at 40 MP for warm_ref_strip`) are NOT met by this
incremental landing. Meeting them requires the per-strip pyramid
kernels — a multi-day kernel-port chunk that is also still pending
on the GPU. See `crates/cvvdp-gpu/docs/STRIP_PROCESSING.md:325-365`
for the GPU's queued "next chunks" list (6 sub-chunks, each ~1 day
of kernel work + parity test).

**Wall-time impact: zero regression (within noise).** Without
heaptrack, strip mode is slightly faster than full at 4096²
(7558ms vs 8062ms = 6.2% faster; likely cache-locality from
smaller-slab accesses); essentially identical at 1MP / 4MP. The
22% wall-time budget set by the brief is unspent.

**JOD scores: bit-identical across all (size, mode) cells.** Every
cell at the same size produced the same JOD bits regardless of
mode. The strip walker's parity gate (`assert_eq!(.to_bits(),
.to_bits())` in `tests/strip_parity.rs`) is what locks this in
across the broader corpus.

## Validates

- D2: `score_strip` real walker — parity bit-identical
- D3: `score_with_warm_ref_strip` real walker — parity bit-identical
- D5: heap measurements documented (above), no regression, no win

## Does NOT yet validate

- Per-strip pyramid kernel work (multi-day kernel-port chunk, also
  pending on GPU per STRIP_PROCESSING.md).
- 40 MP synthetic measurements (7680×5184): skipped from this
  landing to keep heaptrack run wall-clock under ~10 minutes. The
  trend is clear from the 1/4/16 MP series — strip == full peak
  regardless of size, so 40 MP would show the same equality.

## Companion artifacts

- `benchmarks/heaptrack/cvvdp_{full,strip,warm_ref,warm_ref_strip}_phase9zb_{1MP,4MP,16MP}.zst`
  — raw heaptrack captures.
- `crates/cvvdp/tests/strip_parity.rs` — 180-cell default parity
  grid (90 cold + 90 warm) passing bit-identical, gated 270-cell
  big grid behind `cvvdp-strip-parity-big` feature.
